I. 1 Since the victor can subject individuals to personal servi- tude, it is not sui-prizing that he should be allowed to reduce a body of men, whether they be a State, or part of a State, to a servitude, either civil or domestic, or mixed. This is the argument used by some one in Seneca: That he is my slave whom I have bouyht by the laws of war, is α rule expedient for you Atheozians ,· otherwise your empire which has been qained by war is reduced within its ancient Zimits. And accordingly, Tel-tullian says that empire is sought by arms and extended by victories: and Quintilian, that kingdoms, peoples, the boundaries of nations and of cities, are defined by wars.
